The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Saturday, August 28, 2004 				 Mosque blasts
 OUR CORRESPONDENT 																								Mumbai, Aug. 27: Eighteen people were injured in two blasts in Jalna and Poorna towns in Maharashtra today. 																								The bomb blasts occurred within 15 minutes of each other and were both targeted at mosques, prompting speculation that these were attempts to whip up communal tension on the eve of Assembly elections.																								Around 1.45 pm, unidentified assailants riding a motorcycle hurled crude bombs at Kadriya Masjid in Jalna town of Jalna district, about 450 km from Mumbai. The attack injured five persons. About 15 minutes later, unidentified persons on a bike threw bombs at a mosque in Poorna town in Parbhani district, about 560 km from Mumbai.																								The blasts took place when people had gathered to offer Friday prayers.																								Residents of the two towns went on a rampage, setting fire to vehicles, including state transport buses.																								Both the towns are under curfew, but police said the situation is under control. 																								Home minister R.R. Patil said: It is clearly an attempt to create trouble before the elections. 
